// AI Agent Foundations for Hackathons - Question Bank (GIFT)

::AG01_AgentDefinition::
An AI agent is best described as software that:
{
=Receives input, follows instructions, may use tools, and returns output
~Stores files only and never produces responses
~Replaces every cloud service in the system
~Is always correct if it uses a large model
}

::AG02_InputInstructionToolOutput::
Which set names the most useful beginner mental model for an agent?
{
=Input, instructions, tools, output
~Desktop, browser, wallpaper, battery
~Tickets, sprint, epic, release
~Tab, window, bookmark, URL
}

::AG03_NotMagic::
Why is it useful to remember that an agent is not magic?
{
=Because errors can come from prompts, tools, data, or setup
~Because it means the app never needs testing
~Because it proves the agent should work offline
~Because it removes the need for instructions
}

::AG04_ReadmeFirst::
Before editing a starter agent project, what is the best first step?
{
=Read the README and understand setup requirements
~Rename all source files
~Delete unused folders immediately
~Open random files until something looks familiar
}

::AG05_RunBeforeChange::
Why should beginners try to run the starter project before changing it?
{
=It helps isolate later failures caused by your edits
~It guarantees there will never be bugs
~It automatically writes documentation
~It creates cloud credentials for you
}

::AG06_BootstrappingMeaning::
In this course, "bootstrapping" mainly means:
{
=Getting the first working version of the agent running
~Adding every advanced feature before testing
~Publishing the project to production
~Deleting old branches
}

::AG07_SubagentPurpose::
Why add a complaints sub-agent?
{
=To handle complaint-specific logic in a focused way
~To remove the need for a main agent
~To store screenshots in the browser
~To replace the database
}

::AG08_MainVsSubagent::
What is the main agent usually responsible for?
{
=Receiving the overall request and routing work appropriately
~Only formatting spreadsheets
~Only holding API keys
~Only drawing maps
}

::AG09_TestingPattern::
Which is a sensible beginner testing pattern after a major change?
{
=Test a normal input, a messy input, and a routing case
~Test only once at the end of the hackathon
~Skip testing if the code looks clean
~Only test with screenshots
}

::AG10_GenericResponse::
If the sub-agent should have handled a request but the answer is generic, what is a likely issue?
{
=The routing or prompt logic did not trigger correctly
~The browser forgot the page color
~The file explorer is empty
~The learner used too many tabs
}
